0.text: The process begins with receiving a customer order.  Next, stock items are picked based on the order.  The picked items are then packed into parcels.  After packing, the parcels are weighed.  The process then splits into three parallel paths: printing shipping labels, moving parcels to the loading dock, and inspecting the packing quality. Once the shipping labels are printed,  two parallel paths begin: moving the parcels to the loading dock and checking the parcel count.  Once all three parallel paths (printing labels, moving to loading dock, and inspecting quality) are complete, they converge.  Now, the parcels are loaded on the truck and, simultaneously, delivery instructions are sent to the transporter and the order status is updated.  Finally, stock levels are updated, the delivery instructions are sent and when both tasks are complete the process ends.

The process begins with receiving a customer order.  Next, stock items are picked based on the order.  Following this, the picked items are packed into parcels. The packed parcels are then weighed, and shipping labels are printed for them.

At this point, three tasks happen concurrently: the parcels are moved to the loading dock, the number of parcels is checked, and the quality of the packing is inspected. Once all three of these tasks are complete, two more tasks happen concurrently: loading the parcels on the truck and sending delivery instructions to the transporter.  Simultaneously with loading and sending the delivery instructions, the order status is updated. Finally, once the order status is updated and the delivery instructions have been sent, stock levels are updated.  After the stock levels are updated, the process ends.

After the order status is updated, stock levels are also updated.  Finally, once the delivery instructions have been sent and the stock levels have been updated, the process is complete.

The process begins with receiving a shipment request.  Following this, the product availability is checked. Based on the product availability check, the process diverges.

If the product is available in the regional warehouse, the process proceeds to a decision point regarding whether the shipment address is in the Luzern area.

If the address is in the Luzern area, the products are prepared for regional shipment. After preparation, the process ends.

If the address is *not* in the Luzern area, the process goes to a point where the shipment is assembled.  After assembling, the inbound shipment is sent.  This sent shipment is then received, checked, and once again, the process ends.

Returning to the point where product availability is checked: If the product is *not* available in the regional warehouse, the shipment address is checked.  

After checking the shipment address, another decision is made regarding whether the shipment address is in the Luzern area.  If it is, the process flows to the same point where the shipment is assembled, then sent, received, checked, and the process ends, as described previously.

If, however, after checking the shipment address it is found *not* to be in the Luzern area, the process proceeds to the same assembly point. Then it is sent, received, checked, and finally concludes.

1.text:
The process begins with receiving a shipment request.  The next step is to check product availability. Based on the product availability check, the process branches.

If the product *is* available in the regional warehouse, the process moves to a decision point: is the delivery address in the Luzern area?

If the delivery address *is* in Luzern, the products are prepared for regional shipment.  Following this, a final check occurs (although the details of this check aren't specified), and then the process ends.

If the delivery address is *not* in Luzern, the process proceeds as if the product was not available in the regional warehouse.

If the product is *not* available in the regional warehouse, the shipment address is checked. Then, based on the location, a decision is made. If the location is in the Luzern area, the products are prepared for shipment to a particular service station.  After preparation, a final check occurs (again, details aren't specified) and the process ends.

If the location is *not* in the Luzern area, the inbound shipment is assembled. After assembly, the inbound shipment is sent.  This sent shipment is then received, followed by an inbound shipment check.  This check leads to a decision point. If some condition related to this check is met, the products are prepared for shipment to a particular service station. Then, a final check occurs (with unspecified details) and the process ends. If the condition isn't met, the process loops back to assembling the inbound shipment, effectively repeating the steps of sending, receiving, and checking the inbound shipment until the condition at the check is met.

tasks.name: Prepare Products for Shipment to Service Station

2.text:
The process begins with receiving a shipment request.  Next, product availability is checked.  Based on the product availability, the process diverges.

If the product is available in the regional warehouse, the process proceeds to a decision point based on whether the shipment is to the Luzern area.

If the shipment is to the Luzern area, products are prepared for regional shipment. After preparing the products, the process ends.

If the shipment is *not* to the Luzern area,  the process proceeds to a decision point where the inbound shipment is evaluated. The inbound shipment might involve several rounds of receiving, checking, assembling and sending, until a condition is met to stop this cycle.  After this cycle concludes, the process proceeds to prepare products for shipment to a particular service station.  Following this preparation, the process ends.

If the product is *not* available in the regional warehouse, the shipment address is checked. Following this, the Luzern area check is performed and the process follows the same path as described above based on the Luzern area condition.

The process begins with a search for a customer.  After finding a customer, the next step is to make them an offer.  At this point, a decision is needed: did the customer respond to the offer?  If the answer is "yes", then the customer provides an additional request and the process moves to providing details for that request. Following this, there's another decision point: is the customer ready to book?

If the customer decides not to book at this stage, the process ends. However, if they choose to proceed with booking, a booking request is received and the travel is booked.  After booking the travel, a booking confirmation is sent to the customer and, simultaneously, the bill is sent.

Now, another decision point arises: Was the payment received? If “yes,” then the process is complete. If “no,” the customer is contacted. Following the contact, the process goes back to checking for payment and this loops until the payment is received.


If the customer initially did not respond to the offer, the process ends.  Similarly, if after providing details for the customer's additional request, the customer chooses not to book and subsequently doesn't proceed, the process also ends. Finally, If the customer confirms their booking but doesn't provide payment after being contacted, and the loop continues to the decision “Was the payment received?” the process continues until payment is received.

The process begins with searching for a customer.  Following this, an offer is made to the customer.  The next step involves determining if the customer has any additional requests.

If the customer does have additional requests, those details are provided to the customer. After providing these details, the process checks if the customer wants to proceed with a booking.  If the customer doesn't want to book, the process ends. If they do wish to book, a booking request is received.

If the customer didn't have any additional requests after the initial offer, the process also proceeds directly to checking if they want to make a booking. Again, if they don't, the process ends. If they do want to book, a booking request is received.

Once a booking request is received, the travel is booked. After the booking is complete, a booking confirmation is sent to the customer.  Simultaneously, the bill is sent to the customer.

After the bill is sent, a decision point is reached: has the payment been received? If the payment hasn't been received, the customer is contacted. After contacting the customer, the process again checks if the payment has been received. This loop of checking for payment and contacting the customer continues until payment is received.

Once the payment is received,  the travel booking is confirmed (if not already confirmed due to earlier payment).  After confirming the booking the process ends.

The process begins with a search for a customer.  After finding a customer, the next step is to make them an offer.  The response to the offer determines the next course of action. If the customer says yes, they will be asked for additional requests.  If the customer says no, the process ends.

If there are additional requests, the next step is to provide details about those requests. Following this, the customer is asked if they wish to proceed with a booking.  If they don't want to book, the process ends. If they do, a booking request is received.

Once the booking request is received, two things happen simultaneously:  a booking confirmation is sent to the customer, and a bill is sent.  After the bill is sent, the process checks if the payment has been received.

If the payment has not been received, the customer is contacted. After contacting the customer, the process again checks if the payment has been received. This loop of checking for payment and contacting the customer if it hasn't been received continues until the payment is finally received.

Once the payment is received, the travel is booked. Following the booking, the process ends.

The process begins with diagnosing non-specific low back pain.  Following the diagnosis, a decision is made based on the condition of the pain – is it acute or chronic?

If the pain is acute, superficial heat or other non-pharmacological treatments are applied.  After this, there's a decision point: are additional treatments needed?  If yes,  NSAID or SMR is prescribed. Regardless of whether additional treatment is given or not, the process moves to check if treatment is successful or not.

If the initial pain is chronic, exercise or other non-pharmacological treatments are applied.  This leads to an evaluation of whether the treatment was successful.

If the treatment (whether for acute or chronic pain) using non-pharmacological methods and/or NSAID/SMR is not successful, an NSAID is prescribed.  After the NSAID prescription, another check occurs to determine if the treatment was successful. If successful at this stage, the process ends.

If the NSAID treatment is unsuccessful, an opioid is prescribed. After the opioid prescription, regardless of the outcome, the process ends.

The process begins with receiving a production order.  After the order is received, preparation for the order begins.  Next, the process branches into two paths. On one path, raw materials are collected, leading to the cutting stage.  After cutting is complete, the process merges with the other path.  The other path involves adjusting settings and checking if further adjustments are needed. If more adjustments are needed, the process loops back to collecting raw materials. If no further adjustments are needed, the process continues.

Cutting leads to parallel processes of stitching and printing.  Once both stitching and printing are finished, they converge to the completion of production. Following production completion, the product quality is checked and a quality report is created. Based on the quality report, a decision is made: either send the data to the warehouse or adjust settings and restart a portion of the process. If settings adjustments are necessary, the process loops back to gathering raw materials, effectively repeating the cutting, stitching, printing, and production steps.

If the quality report is satisfactory, data is sent to the warehouse, concluding the process.

1.text: The process begins with receiving a production order.  After the order is received, preparation for the production order begins. This preparation step leads to a decision point. If further adjustments are needed, the settings are adjusted, and the process loops back to the decision point after adjustments. This cycle continues until no further adjustments are required.  Once ready, raw materials are collected, leading to the cutting stage.  After cutting, the process splits into two parallel paths: stitching and printing. When both stitching and printing are complete, they converge, and production is finalized. The completed product then undergoes a quality check, followed by the creation of a quality report. The quality report leads to another decision point. If the quality is acceptable, the data is sent to the warehouse, and the process ends. If the quality is not acceptable, the process loops back to adjusting the settings, beginning the production cycle again.

The process begins with a shipment request.  Upon receiving the request, two actions happen in parallel: the goods are packaged and the shipment type is selected.  

When selecting the shipment type, there are two options: regular post or a special carrier. If regular post is chosen, a post label is filled in and insurance is checked. If a special carrier is selected, quotes are requested from different carriers, and a carrier is assigned before preparing the paperwork.

Regardless of the shipping type chosen, the next step is checking the insurance.  If extra insurance is needed, the customer takes it out. If not, the process continues.  This insurance check happens after the post label is filled in for regular post, and after the paperwork is prepared if a special carrier is used.

Once the goods are packaged and the paperwork (including any extra insurance) is finalized, both sets of actions converge, and the paperwork is added to the package. Finally, the package is moved to the pickup area, completing the process.

The process begins with a shipment request.  Upon receiving the request, two parallel processes are initiated: packaging the goods and selecting the kind of shipment.  

The shipment selection determines the next steps. If a special carrier is required, quotes are requested from those carriers. The chosen carrier is then assigned, and the paperwork is prepared.  Alternatively, if regular post is sufficient, a post label is filled in.

After filling in the post label, the insurance is checked.  This leads to a decision regarding extra insurance. If extra insurance is desired, it is taken out. Regardless of this decision, the process converges and continues.

Simultaneously, once the goods are packaged and the paperwork is prepared (following carrier assignment or post label creation), the two parallel processes converge.  The paperwork is added to the package, and finally, the package is moved to the pickup area, concluding the process.

Meanwhile, once the carrier is assigned (if a special carrier was chosen), the necessary paperwork is prepared. Regardless of the shipping method, the paperwork is added to the packaged goods and the package is moved to the pickup area.  After the package reaches the pickup area, the process is complete.

The process begins when a customer makes a request.  The request is then checked. If the request is deemed standard, it proceeds to automatic registration. Otherwise, it goes through manual registration.  Both automatic and manual registrations eventually lead to a point where the system checks if the request is relevant.

If the request is not relevant, a notification is sent to the customer, and the process ends. If the request *is* relevant, it proceeds differently depending on whether it was a standard request or not.  If the request was standard, it goes directly to searching for an attraction provider. If it was a manual request, the process attempts to book the attraction.

After attempting to book, the system checks for availability. If the attraction is not available, the process loops back to searching for an attraction provider. This loop of booking and checking availability continues until an available attraction is found.

If an attraction *is* available, the process continues to receiving a booking confirmation.  Following confirmation, a confirmation is sent to the customer, and the process ends.  

Whether the request was standard or not, if the search for a provider is successful, the process attempts to book the attraction and follows the same availability check and confirmation steps as described above. If no provider is found, a notification is sent to the customer, and the process ends. This ensures all paths ultimately lead to either a successful booking confirmation sent to the customer or a notification of failure.

1.text:
The process begins with receiving a customer request.  This request is then checked.  If the check reveals it's a standard request, the process proceeds to automatic registration. If it's not a standard request, it goes to manual registration.  Both automatic and manual registration converge to a single point where the relevance of the request is evaluated.

If the request is deemed not relevant, a notification is sent to the customer, and the process ends.  However, if the request is relevant, the process branches based on whether it's a standard request or not.  If standard, it proceeds directly to searching for an attraction provider. If not, it first goes through automatic or manual registration (as described earlier) and *then* searches for a provider.

Once a provider search is completed, the process checks if a provider was found. If not, the customer is notified, and the process ends.  If a provider *is* found, the process attempts to book the attraction.

After the booking attempt, the process waits for either a booking confirmation or a rejection.  If a rejection is received, the process loops back to search for a different attraction provider.  This loop continues until either a provider is found and the booking is confirmed *or* no provider can be found.

If a booking confirmation is received, the confirmation is sent to the customer, and the process ends.

The process begins with a customer request.  This request is then checked. If the check reveals it's a standard request, the process proceeds to automatic registration. Otherwise, it goes to manual registration.  Both automatic and manual registration converge at a point where the system determines if the request is relevant.

If the request isn't relevant, the customer receives a notification and the process ends. If the request is relevant, the system again checks if it was a standard request. If so, it moves to automatic registration, then checks relevance again, creating a loop.

Assuming the request is deemed relevant, the system searches for an attraction provider.  If a provider is found, the system attempts to book the attraction. If the booking is successful, the customer receives a booking confirmation and then a final confirmation, concluding the process. However, if the booking is rejected, the process loops back to search for an attraction provider.

If no provider is found, the system informs the customer with a notification and the process ends. Finally, whether a final confirmation is sent or a notification about provider unavailability, the process reaches its conclusion.

The process begins with retrieving breached data.  Simultaneously, the breached subjects are also retrieved.  These two actions happen in parallel.  Once both are complete, two parallel paths are initiated: data loss limitation and notifying the national authority.

After the national authority is notified, the stolen data is evaluated.  Based on the evaluation, a decision is made: Are the stolen data exploitable?  If yes, the process moves to check if the data controller has high security standards. If no, the process skips this check and moves directly to the next step, which is common to both paths coming out of the decision.

The next step is a decision point: does the data subject have to be notified? This step can be reached either after the stolen data evaluation and security standard check or directly from the stolen data evaluation if the data are deemed not exploitable. Regardless of the path taken to this decision, If yes,  a notification is sent to the data subject. If no, the process ends.

If a notification is sent, the process waits to receive notification back regarding the request.  Based on this received notification, the process ends.

1.text:
The process begins with retrieving the breached data.  Immediately after, the breached subjects are also retrieved. These two actions happen sequentially.  Once both sets of information are gathered, two parallel processes begin: Data Loss Limitation and notifying the National Authority.  After the National Authority is notified, the stolen data is evaluated.  This evaluation leads to a decision: "Are the stolen data exploitable?"

If the stolen data are NOT exploitable, the security standard is evaluated. This evaluation leads to another decision:  "Does the data controller have a high security standard?" If YES, a request is made to determine whether the breached data has to be communicated to the data subject. After the notification for this request is received, another decision point is reached: "The data subject has to be notified?"  If YES, the process follows the same path as if the stolen data WERE exploitable (described below). If NO, the process ends.

If the data controller does NOT have a high security standard, or if the stolen data ARE exploitable (from the earlier decision), the process converges to a single path.  This path involves sending a notification to the data subjects, followed by a check if notification was successfully sent. Once confirmed, the process ends.

tasks.name: Request to determine whether the breached data has to be communicated to the data subject

2.text:
The process begins with retrieving the breached data.  Immediately after, the breached subjects are also retrieved. These two actions happen sequentially.  Then, two parallel processes kick off:  Data loss limitation efforts begin, and simultaneously, the national authority is notified.

Once the national authority has been notified, the stolen data is evaluated. Based on this evaluation, a decision is made: Are the stolen data exploitable? If yes, a further decision point is reached about whether the affected data subjects have to be notified.  If the decision is yes, a notification is sent, and after the notification is sent, a final check occurs. This check, whose details are not explicitly modeled here, appears to finalize the process. If, at the first decision point, the stolen data were deemed *not* exploitable, the process evaluates the security standard.

In parallel with the data loss limitation activities, after the breached subjects are retrieved, a decision gateway assesses if the data controller has a high security standard. If yes, a request is made to determine whether the breached data has to be communicated to the data subject. A notification for the request is then received, and this feeds into the same decision point we reached earlier – whether the data subject has to be notified.  If the decision is again yes, the notification is sent, and the process continues to the final check.

If, however, the data controller does *not* have a high security standard, the process merges with the path followed when the stolen data were deemed exploitable, and the same decision point regarding notification of data subjects is reached again. Following that decision, notification may or may not be sent, and the process concludes with the final check. If, at the first decision, about whether stolen data are exploitable, and if the data subject has to notified the answer is no, then the final check occurs.

tasks.name: Request to determine whether breached data has to be communicated

The process begins when a patient arrives at the hospital.  The first step is for the patient to stay in the front area.  Next, the patient visits the nurse who checks their current state.

Based on the patient's state, there are two paths. If the patient is ok, they are sent home, ending the process. If not, they proceed to insurance verification.

If the patient's insurance is confirmed, the next step is to determine if the patient is registered with the hospital. If they are not registered, they are registered first. Regardless of their prior registration status, they are then booked for a doctor's appointment. After the booking, the fee is paid, and the patient moves on to see the doctor, who examines them.

Following the examination, there are three possible routes:

1. **Healthy:** The patient is deemed healthy and sent home, concluding the process.
2. **Needs Hospitalization:** The patient is hospitalized, then goes to the front area to pay before going home, thus ending the process for them.
3. **Needs Medicine:**  The patient is sent to the pharmacy, where they visit, order medicine, and pay for it. Finally, after receiving the medicine, they go home, finishing the process.

1.text:
The process begins when a patient arrives at the hospital.  The first step is for the patient to stay at the front desk. Next, the patient visits a nurse who checks their current health state.

Based on the patient's condition, the process diverges. If the patient is deemed healthy enough to go home, they are sent home, ending the process.  If further examination is needed, the process continues.

If the patient requires further examination, the hospital must then determine the patient's registration status. If the patient is not registered, they are registered.  Regardless of pre-existing registration or after completing new registration, the patient proceeds to check their insurance.

After insurance is checked, the decision branches based on whether the patient's insurance is accepted or not. Assuming it is, the patient then books an appointment with a doctor. If the insurance isn't accepted, then the patient must pay a fee before booking an appointment with the doctor. After the appointment is booked, the patient will be examined by the doctor.

Following the doctor's examination, the process branches again based on the doctor's assessment. Three possibilities exist: the patient needs hospitalization, medication, or is healthy enough to go home.

If the patient needs to be hospitalized, they are hospitalized, and then after discharge, they pay a fee before going home, ending the process.

If the patient needs medicine, they are sent to the pharmacy.  At the pharmacy, they order their medicine, then pay for it, and finally, they receive the medicine.  After receiving the medicine, the patient goes home, ending the process.

If the patient is healthy after the doctor’s examination, they are simply sent home, ending the process.

gateways.name: Patient healthy enough to go home?

2.text:
The process begins when a patient arrives at the hospital.  The first step is for the patient to stay in the front area. Next, the patient visits the nurse, who then checks the patient's insurance. Following this check, there is a decision point regarding the patient's insurance coverage. 

If the insurance is valid, the patient proceeds to registration.  If the patient is not registered, they are registered with the hospital. Whether the patient was already registered or just newly registered, they then proceed to pay the hospital fee. After paying the fee, the patient is booked for a doctor's appointment.  This booking leads to the patient being examined by the doctor.

After the examination, another decision point occurs based on the doctor's diagnosis.  There are three possible paths:

1. If the patient is healthy, they are sent home.
2. If the patient needs hospitalization, they are hospitalized and then, eventually, they are also sent home as they get better and leave.
3. If the patient needs medicine, they are sent to the pharmacy.  At the pharmacy, the patient orders medicine, pays for the medicine, and receives the medicine.  Finally, the patient leaves the hospital after getting their medicine, and the process ends.


If the initial insurance check reveals invalid insurance, the patient's state is checked.  Following this check, there's another decision point: if the patient's condition is okay, they are sent home, and the process ends. If their condition is not okay, they are checked for registration, and the process loops back to the registration check, as described earlier.  This loop continues until either the patient's condition improves enough to be sent home directly after the state check, or their insurance issue is resolved. After any of the last steps are executed, and the patient is discharged, the entire process ends.

The process begins with a pregnant woman calling the hospital.  The hospital then makes a decision about whether to accept the patient.

If the patient is accepted, she is added to the list of patients and undergoes a patient control check. If the pregnancy is less than 8 months along, the patient is added back to the patient list for further monitoring and control checks. This loop continues until the pregnancy reaches 8 months.  If the pregnancy is in or beyond the 8th month, the hospital calls the patient to come in.  After arrival, the patient is hospitalized, gives birth, and then undergoes a health check for both the patient and baby.  

If after birth the patient and baby are healthy, the patient is discharged and enters post-hospitalization care. This eventually concludes the process.  However, if the patient or baby are not healthy after birth, they receive special treatment. After the special treatment, the patient is discharged and the process ends.

If the initial decision is to not accept the patient, the process ends immediately.

The process begins with packaging the product.  Next, the product is shipped.  The shipping process involves deciding where the delivery should take place: at the recipient's door or at a designated station.

If door delivery is chosen, the process checks if the recipient is present. If the recipient is present, the delivery is considered successful, and the process ends. If the recipient is *not* present, a pick-up receipt is printed and subsequently posted to the recipient.  After this, the package is rerouted to the closest station, and the recipient can pick it up there.  Once at the station, the process continues to the next stage.

If station delivery is chosen initially, the process skips the recipient presence check and moves directly to the next stage.

This next stage, regardless of whether the package was delivered to the door or a station, involves the recipient receiving the product.  At this point, there's a check to see if the product is damaged.

If the product is *not* damaged, the process ends successfully. If the product *is* damaged, the recipient returns the product. The process then ends, likely signifying an unsuccessful delivery or the initiation of a return/replacement process.

The process begins with getting temperature values.  If these values are within an acceptable range (greater than 10 and less than 15), a standard notification is generated. Otherwise, several parallel processes are initiated.

One branch of this parallel process involves getting the container status and then estimating that status. Based on the estimated status, if it's "ok," the process merges back to the main flow.  If it's "not ok," a container change request is generated, which also merges back to the main flow.

A second parallel branch starts by getting the client's location and then estimating the distance. If the distance is less than 300km, the delivery time is estimated. If the distance is 300km or greater, or if the estimated delivery time is not "ok," a route change request is generated. Regardless of the distance or delivery time estimation, this branch also merges back to the main flow.

The third and final parallel branch involves getting the goods status and then estimating that status.  If damage is detected, the damage is then evaluated.  If the goods are "ruined," a removal request is generated. If the goods are "compromised," a price change request is generated.  If there is no damage, or after a removal or price change request is generated, this branch merges back with the others.

After all three parallel branches complete, any generated messages (standard notifications, container change requests, route change requests, removal requests, or price change requests) are sent.  Finally, the process ends.

The process begins with getting temperature values.  Based on these values, the process branches. If the temperature is between 10 and 15, a standard notification is generated.  Otherwise, if the temperature falls outside this range, several parallel actions are initiated:

1. **Container Information:** The container status is retrieved, and simultaneously, a container status estimate is made. The estimated status is then checked.  If it's "ok," the process moves to the next parallel branch. If it's "nok," a container change request is generated, which is then evaluated and merged back into the main flow.

2. **Delivery Information:**  In parallel with the container actions, the client's location is obtained.  This is used to estimate the distance and the delivery time. If the distance is less than 300km, the estimated delivery time is then checked.  If the delivery time is "ok," the process continues. If it's "nok" or the distance is 300km or more, a route change request is generated and eventually rejoins the main flow.

3. **Goods Information:** The final parallel branch involves getting the goods status and, concurrently, estimating the goods status.  If any damage is detected in the estimated status, the extent of the damage is evaluated. If the goods are "ruined," a removal request is generated. If the goods are "compromised," a price change request is generated.  If there is no damage, the process simply proceeds.

Once all three parallel branches (container, delivery, and goods) are complete, all generated messages (standard notifications, container change requests, route change requests, removal requests, and price change requests) are sent. After the messages are sent, the process ends.

Regardless of whether the container status is "ok" or "nok," this branch of the parallel process converges to the point where parallel processes combine and continue as a single process.

The second parallel process starts by getting the client's location, followed by estimating the delivery time.  If the estimated duration is "ok," the process proceeds. If not, a route change request is generated.  Regardless, this path converges back to the point where parallel processes combine.

The third parallel process initiates by getting the goods status and then estimating it.  If damages are detected ("yes"), they are evaluated. If not ("no"), the process skips evaluation.  If the damage is "ruined," a removal request is generated. If the damage is "compromised," a price change request is generated.  Regardless of the evaluation outcome, this path also converges back to the point where the parallel processes come together as a single flow.

After all three parallel processes complete, the generated messages (which can include a standard notification, container change request, route change request, removal request, or price change request, depending on the conditions met throughout the process), are sent.  Once the messages are sent, the process ends.

The process begins when consent to use is required.  Several actions then happen simultaneously:

1. We add information about the logic, significance, and consequences of the data processing.
2. We check if it's possible to determine how long the personal data will be stored.
3. We also check whether the data has been obtained directly from the data subject.
4. We check if personal data can be transferred internationally.
5. We check if there are any recipients for the data.
6. We check if there are legitimate interests for processing the data.
7. We retrieve the processing's legal basis.
8. We retrieve the purposes of the processing.
9. We begin collecting the identity and contact details of the Data Protection Officer (DPO).

After checking if it's possible to determine the data storage period, we decide whether it's possible. If it *is* possible, we retrieve the period. If it's *not* possible, we retrieve the criteria used to determine the period.  Both paths eventually lead to the same point where we go back to complete the actions started earlier.

After checking if the data was obtained from the data subject, we either retrieve the source of the data (if it *wasn't* obtained directly) or proceed with other actions if it *was* obtained directly.  Again, both paths rejoin the main flow.

After collecting the DPO's identity and contact details, we ask for the DPO details and simultaneously wait to receive them. Once received, these details are combined with the other information gathered in the parallel tasks.

Once all the parallel tasks (including adding descriptions of data rights, checking for international transfers, checking for recipients, and retrieving legal basis and purposes) are finished, we proceed to prepare a consent request and then ask for consent.

If the person consents, we collect their consent information.  If they refuse, we receive their negation.  Both outcomes lead to the final step, where the process ends.

1.text:
The process begins when consent to use is required.  Several actions then happen simultaneously:

1. We add information about the logic, significance, and consequences of processing data. This leads to a point where several other parallel actions are initiated.
2. We check if it is possible to determine how long personal data will be stored.  This leads to a decision:
    * **If it *is* possible**: We retrieve the period. After this, another check occurs. 
    * **If it is *not* possible**: We retrieve the criteria used to determine the period. After this, the same check from the previous option is reached. This check feeds back into the parallel actions initiated after step 1.

The parallel actions after adding the processing data information in step 1 include:

* Adding the existence of rights to rectify, access, and erase personal data.  Each of these additions independently feeds into the parallel actions that follow step 1's initial actions.
* Adding the existence of the right to data portability, the right to withdraw consent, and the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority. These also each feed into the same parallel actions that follow step 1.
* Checking if the data has been obtained from the data subject.  This leads to another decision:
    * **If the data *was* obtained from the data subject**:  We proceed directly to the parallel actions that follow step 1.
    * **If the data was *not* obtained from the data subject**: We retrieve the source from which the personal data originated. This then leads to the parallel actions.
* Checking if personal data can be transferred internationally.  This leads to a decision:
    * **If data *can* be transferred**: We add "personal data will be transferred internationally", which then feeds into the parallel actions that follow step 1.
    * **If data *cannot* be transferred**: We skip directly to the parallel actions.
* Checking if recipients are present.  This leads to a decision:
    * **If recipients are *present***: We retrieve the recipients.  This then feeds into the parallel actions.
    * **If recipients are *not present***: We go directly to the parallel actions.
* Checking if legitimate interests are present. This leads to a decision:
    * **If legitimate interests are *present***: We retrieve the legitimate interests, feeding into the parallel actions.
    * **If legitimate interests are *not present***:  We go directly to the parallel actions that follow step 1.
* Retrieving the processing legal basis and the processing purposes. Each of these independently feeds into the parallel actions.
* Finally, we retrieve identity and contact details and concurrently ask for DPO details. The retrieval of identity and contact details leads to two more concurrent actions:
* Retrieving the identity and contact details also leads to asking for consent.
* In parallel with asking for DPO details, receiving the details back from the DPO feeds into the parallel actions that follow step 1. 

Following the confluence of all these parallel activities after step 1, we collect consent information. This then leads to asking for consent, resulting in two possible outcomes:

* **Consent is received**: The process ends.
* **Consent is not received (negation)**: The process ends.

2.text:
The process begins when consent to use is required.  Several actions then happen simultaneously:

1. We add information about the logic, significance, and consequences of data processing.  After this, we proceed to check if it's possible to determine how long personal data will be stored.

2. At the same time as step 1, we also check if the data has been obtained directly from the data subject.

3. Alongside steps 1 and 2, we also do the following in parallel:
    * Add information about the right to rectify personal data.
    * Add information about the right to access personal data.
    * Add information about the right to erase personal data.
    * Add information about the right to data portability.
    * Add information about the right to withdraw consent.
    * Add information about the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority.
    * Check if personal data can be transferred internationally.
    * Check if there are any recipients of the data.
    * Check if there are legitimate interests for processing the data.
    * Retrieve the legal basis for processing.
    * Retrieve the purposes of processing.
    * Retrieve the identity and contact details of the data controller.
    * Begin the process to identify a Data Protection Officer (DPO).

Let's look at some of these parallel branches in more detail:

* **Data storage period:** If it's *not* possible to determine the storage period, we retrieve the criteria used to determine it.  If it *is* possible to determine the storage period, we retrieve the period itself.  In either case, after retrieving the relevant information (criteria or period), these branches converge.

* **Data source:** If the data was *not* obtained from the data subject, we retrieve the source of the data. If the data *was* obtained from the data subject, we skip this step. Both paths then converge.

* **Data recipients:** If recipients are present, we retrieve them. If not, we skip this step. Both paths then converge.

* **Legitimate interests:** If legitimate interests are present, we retrieve them.  If not, we skip this step. Both paths then converge.

* **Data Protection Officer (DPO):**  After initiating the process to identify a DPO, we request their details.  Upon receiving these details, this information is added to the main process flow.

Once all of the above parallel branches have completed, several actions occur in parallel, including gathering all the collected information and beginning the consent process. This involves collecting consent information, asking for consent, and then waiting for a response.

The process then splits based on the response:

* **Consent given:** If consent is given, the process ends.
* **Consent denied:** If consent is denied, the process also ends.

The process begins with the receipt of a data subject request.  Following this, a check is performed to determine if the withdrawn data is relevant. This check leads to two possible paths.

If the withdrawn data is deemed relevant, the user is informed that withdrawing the data will stop all running business processes. Then, the user receives a notification asking whether they wish to continue with the withdrawal.  If the user chooses to continue, the system stops running any business processes that use the withdrawn data. Then, the system stops using the withdrawn data altogether, and the process ends. Conversely, if the user chooses not to continue after being informed of the consequences, the system communicates the withdrawal, and the process ends.


If the withdrawn data is *not* deemed relevant, the system stops using the withdrawn data, communicates the withdrawal, and the process ends.

1.text:
The process begins with the receipt of a data subject request.  Following this, a check is performed to see if the withdrawn data is relevant.  If the data is deemed relevant, the user is informed that withdrawing the data will stop all running business processes. After the user is informed, they are asked to confirm whether they want to continue with the withdrawal. If the user chooses to continue, any business processes using the withdrawn data are stopped.  After stopping the processes, the withdrawn data is no longer used, and the withdrawal is communicated. Regardless of whether the user chooses to continue or not after being informed, this communication step happens. The entire process then concludes.

However, if the initial check determines that the withdrawn data is *not* relevant, the data is immediately no longer used, and the withdrawal is communicated.  Again, the process ends after the communication.

2.text:
The process begins with the receipt of a data subject request. Following this, a check is performed to determine if the withdrawn data is relevant.  If the data is deemed relevant, the user is informed that withdrawing the data will stop all running business processes.  After informing the user, the system waits for the user to confirm whether they want to continue or not with the withdrawal.

If the user decides to continue, the system stops any running business processes that are using the withdrawn data. Then the system proceeds to stop using the withdrawn data altogether. Finally, the withdrawal is communicated.

Alternatively, if the user decides not to continue after being warned, the withdrawal is communicated directly without stopping any processes or ceasing the use of the data.  

In the case where the withdrawn data was initially deemed irrelevant, the system skips the warning, confirmation, and stopping of business processes, and proceeds directly to stopping the use of the withdrawn data, communicating the withdrawal, and ending the process.
